snippet.textDisplay:
My mom has Alzheimers and if she could have learned to use this technology to remember things for her it would have helped her.

Unfortunately she’s now in a phase where this can’t help anymore. She doesn’t even remember what she did 5 minutes ago.

If this thing does what the ad shows and you have a relative in the early stages of Alzheimers; please give them this. (or anything with similar functionality)

It’s less hard to admit to a device that you need to remember something than to a loved one. And if they learn to use it early enough my hope is that knowledge is there to stay.

snippet.textDisplay: As commented on LinkedIn: "That commercial was garbage. Who needs an existential crisis about a withering death by senility during the Super Bowl? When I tune in to the Super Bowl for athleticism at peak human levels, pomp and circumstance, jet fighter flyovers, life, youth, pageantry, glamour, and fierce competition, the last thing I want to see is Google peddling AI as a phantom nurse that doesn't hold your hand while you're dying of Alzheimer's. W T actual F? This commercial is about dying alone with only an uncaring, soulless computer to listen to you. Computers don't care about you."
